  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1956 (Money Laundering Control Act)\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1957\n- The USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. State Level Statutes:\n- Most states have their own money laundering prevention laws\n- These often mirror federal statutes but can have specific additional provisions\n\n3. Key Federal Provisions:\n- Criminalizing financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities\n- Requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establishing reporting requirements for cash transactions over $10,000\n- Implementing penalties including fines and imprisonment\n\n4. International Frameworks:\n- The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) guidelines\n- Various international anti-money laundering treaties\n\nThese statutes generally aim to:\n- Detect and prevent money laundering\n- Prosecute individuals and organizations engaged in such activities\n- Protect the financial system from criminal exploitation\n\nPenalties can include substantial fines and significant prison sentences depending on the specific circumstances and amount involved.",
